                    <h1>BOUNCING BACK</h1>
                    <p>Loss of habitat and poaching have made Amur leopards one of the rarest wild cats on Earth—and the world’s rarest leopard.
                        Thanks in part to a newly established national park along the Russian and Chinese border, however, Amur leopards are clawing their way back.
                        Since the 647,400-acre refuge dubbed Land of the Leopard National Park was created in 2012, the Amur leopard population has jumped to about
                        80 individuals in 2018, up from only about 30 in the early 2000s. Officials believe that effective law enforcement in the park will help keep
                        the population climbing. So hopefully, even more of these leopards will be spotted soon.</p>
